# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acid-base-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In chemistry, an **acid–base reaction** is a chemical reaction that occurs between an acid and a base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] It can be used to determine pH via titration.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Several theoretical frameworks provide alternative conceptions of the reaction mechanisms and their application in solving related problems; these are called the acid–base theories, for example, Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Their importance becomes apparent in analyzing acid–base reactions for gaseous or liquid species, or when acid or base character may be somewhat less apparent.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The first of these concepts was provided by the French chemist Antoine Lavoisier, around 1776.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] It is important to think of the acid–base reaction models as theories that complement each other.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] For example, the current Lewis model has the broadest definition of what an acid and base are, with the Brønsted–Lowry theory being a subset of what acids and bases are, and the Arrhenius theory being the most restrictive.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Arrhenius theory describes an acid as a substance that increases the concentration of hydrogen ions (H3O+ or H+) in a solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A base is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide ions (OH-) in a solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] However, Arrhenius's definition only applies to substances that are in water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The concept of an acid–base reaction was first proposed in 1754 by Guillaume-François Rouelle, who introduced the word "base" into chemistry to mean a substance which reacts with an acid to give it solid form (as a salt).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The first scientific concept of acids and bases was provided by Lavoisier in around 1776.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Lavoisier definition held for over 30 years, until the 1810 article and subsequent lectures by Sir Humphry Davy in which he proved the lack of oxygen in hydrogen sulfide (H2S), hydrogen telluride (H2Te), and the hydrohalic acids.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] However, Davy failed to develop a new theory, concluding that "acidity does not depend upon any particular elementary substance, but upon peculiar arrangement of various substances".
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] One notable modification of oxygen theory was provided by Jöns Jacob Berzelius, who stated that acids are oxides of nonmetals while bases are oxides of metals.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In 1838, Justus von Liebig proposed that an acid is a hydrogen-containing compound whose hydrogen can be replaced by a metal.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This redefinition was based on his extensive work on the chemical composition of organic acids, finishing the doctrinal shift from oxygen-based acids to hydrogen-based acids started by Davy.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Liebig's definition, while completely empirical, remained in use for almost 50 years until the adoption of the Arrhenius definition.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The first modern definition of acids and bases in molecular terms was devised by Svante Arrhenius.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A hydrogen theory of acids, it followed from his 1884 work with Friedrich Wilhelm Ostwald in establishing the presence of ions in aqueous solution and led to Arrhenius receiving the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1903.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This causes the protonation of water, or the creation of the hydronium (H3O+) ion.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Thus, in modern times, the symbol H+ is interpreted as a shorthand for H3O+, because it is now known that a bare proton does not exist as a free species in aqueous solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This is the species which is measured by pH indicators to measure the acidity or basicity of a solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Arrhenius definitions of acidity and alkalinity are restricted to aqueous solutions and are not valid for most non-aqueous solutions, and refer to the concentration of the solvent ions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Under this definition, pure H2SO4 and HCl dissolved in toluene are not acidic, and molten NaOH and solutions of calcium amide in liquid ammonia are not alkaline.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This led to the development of the Brønsted–Lowry theory and subsequent Lewis theory to account for these non-aqueous exceptions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The reaction of an acid with a base is called a neutralization reaction.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In this traditional representation an acid–base neutralization reaction is formulated as a double-replacement reaction.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The modifier (aq) in this equation was implied by Arrhenius, rather than included explicitly.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] It indicates that the substances are dissolved in water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Though all three substances, HCl, NaOH and NaCl are capable of existing as pure compounds, in aqueous solutions they are fully dissociated into the aquated ions H+, Cl−, Na+ and OH−.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is used to cause the dough for breads and cakes to "rise" by creating millions of tiny carbon dioxide bubbles.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is not to be confused with baking soda, which is sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is a mixture of baking soda (sodium bicarbonate) and acidic salts.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The bubbles are created because, when the baking powder is combined with water, the sodium bicarbonate and acid salts react to produce gaseous carbon dioxide.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Whether commercially or domestically prepared, the principles behind baking powder formulations remain the same.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The real reactions are more complicated because the acids are complicated.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A typical formulation (by weight) could call for 30% sodium bicarbonate, 5–12% monocalcium phosphate, and 21–26% sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Alternately, a commercial baking powder might use sodium acid pyrophosphate as one of the two acidic components instead of sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Another typical acid in such formulations is cream of tartar (KC4H5O6), a derivative of tartaric acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] An acid–base reaction is, thus, the removal of a proton from the acid and its addition to the base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The removal of a proton from an acid produces its *conjugate base*, which is the acid with a proton removed.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The reception of a proton by a base produces its *conjugate acid*, which is the base with a proton added.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Unlike the previous definitions, the Brønsted–Lowry definition does not refer to the formation of salt and solvent, but instead to the formation of *conjugate acids* and *conjugate bases*, produced by the transfer of a proton from the acid to the base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In this approach, acids and bases are fundamentally different in behavior from salts, which are seen as electrolytes, subject to the theories of Debye, Onsager, and others.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] An acid and a base react not to produce a salt and a solvent, but to form a new acid and a new base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The concept of neutralization is thus absent.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base behavior is formally independent of any solvent, making it more all-encompassing than the Arrhenius model.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The calculation of pH under the Arrhenius model depended on alkalis (bases) dissolving in water (aqueous solution).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Brønsted–Lowry model expanded what could be pH tested using insoluble and soluble solutions (gas, liquid, solid).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The general formula for acid–base reactions according to the Brønsted–Lowry definition is: ${\ce {HA + B -> BH+ + A-}}$ where HA represents the acid, B represents the base, BH+ represents the conjugate acid of B, and A− represents the conjugate base of HA.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The removal of H+ from the HCl produces the chloride ion, Cl−, the conjugate base of the acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The addition of H+ to the H2O (acting as a base) forms the hydronium ion, H3O+, the conjugate acid of the base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Water is amphoteric – that is, it can act as both an acid and a base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Here, one molecule of water acts as an acid, donating an H+ and forming the conjugate base, OH−, and a second molecule of water acts as a base, accepting the H+ ion and forming the conjugate acid, H3O+.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In this example, a water molecule is split into a hydrogen cation, which is donated to a pyridine molecule, and a hydroxide ion.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In the Brønsted–Lowry model, the solvent does not necessarily have to be water, as is required by the Arrhenius Acid–Base model.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] An H+ ion is removed from acetic acid, forming its conjugate base, the acetate ion, CH3COO−.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The addition of an H+ ion to an ammonia molecule of the solvent creates its conjugate acid, the ammonium ion, NH+4.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Brønsted–Lowry model calls hydrogen-containing substances (like HCl) acids.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Thus, some substances, which many chemists considered to be acids, such as SO3 or BCl3, are excluded from this classification due to lack of hydrogen.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The hydrogen requirement of Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry was removed by the Lewis definition of acid–base reactions, devised by Gilbert N.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Lewis in 1923, in the same year as Brønsted–Lowry, but it was not elaborated by him until 1938.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Instead of defining acid–base reactions in terms of protons or other bonded substances, the Lewis definition defines a base (referred to as a *Lewis base*) to be a compound that can donate an *electron pair*, and an acid (a *Lewis acid*) to be a compound that can receive this electron pair.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] For example, boron trifluoride, BF3 is a typical Lewis acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] It can accept a pair of electrons as it has a vacancy in its octet.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The fluoride ion has a full octet and can donate a pair of electrons.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Thus ${\ce {BF3 + F- -> BF4-}}$ is a typical Lewis acid, Lewis base reaction.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] All compounds of group 13 elements with a formula AX3 can behave as Lewis acids.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Similarly, compounds of group 15 elements with a formula DY3, such as amines, NR3, and phosphines, PR3, can behave as Lewis bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Adducts between them have the formula X3A←DY3 with a dative covalent bond, shown symbolically as ←, between the atoms A (acceptor) and D (donor).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Compounds of group 16 with a formula DX2 may also act as Lewis bases; in this way, a compound like an ether, R2O, or a thioether, R2S, can act as a Lewis base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Lewis definition is not limited to these examples.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] For instance, carbon monoxide acts as a Lewis base when it forms an adduct with boron trifluoride, of formula F3B←CO.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Adducts involving metal ions are referred to as co-ordination compounds; each ligand donates a pair of electrons to the metal ion.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The reaction ${\ce {[Ag(H2O)4]+ + 2 NH3 -> [Ag(NH3)2]+ + 4 H2O}}$ can be seen as an acid–base reaction in which a stronger base (ammonia) replaces a weaker one (water).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Lewis and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are consistent with each other since the reaction ${\ce {H+ + OH- <=> H2O}}$ is an acid–base reaction in both theories.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] One of the limitations of the Arrhenius definition is its reliance on water solutions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Edward Curtis Franklin studied the acid–base reactions in liquid ammonia in 1905 and pointed out the similarities to the water-based Arrhenius theory.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Germann, working with liquid phosgene, COCl 2, formulated the solvent-based theory in 1925, thereby generalizing the Arrhenius definition to cover aprotic solvents.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvonium ions and a decrease in the concentration of solvate ions is defined as an *acid*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvate ions and a decrease in the concentration of the solvonium ions is defined as a *base*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Thus, in liquid ammonia, KNH2 (supplying NH−2) is a strong base, and NH4NO3 (supplying NH+4) is a strong acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In liquid sulfur dioxide (SO2), thionyl compounds (supplying SO2+) behave as acids, and sulfites (supplying SO2−3) behave as bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] On the other hand, solvent system theory has been criticized as being too general to be useful.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Also, it has been thought that there is something intrinsically acidic about hydrogen compounds, a property not shared by non-hydrogenic solvonium salts.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This acid–base theory was a revival of the oxygen theory of acids and bases proposed by German chemist Hermann Lux in 1939, further improved by Håkon Flood c.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] 1947 and is still used in modern geochemistry and electrochemistry of molten salts.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This definition describes an acid as an oxide ion (O2−) acceptor and a base as an oxide ion donor.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This theory is also useful in the systematisation of the reactions of noble gas compounds, especially the xenon oxides, fluorides, and oxofluorides.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Mikhail Usanovich developed a general theory that does not restrict acidity to hydrogen-containing compounds, but his approach, published in 1938, was even more general than Lewis theory.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Usanovich's theory can be summarized as defining an acid as anything that accepts negative species or donates positive ones, and a base as the reverse.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This defined the concept of redox (oxidation-reduction) as a special case of acid–base reactions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In 1963, Ralph Pearson proposed a qualitative concept known as the Hard and Soft Acids and Bases principle. later made quantitative with help of Robert Parr in 1984.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] 'Hard' applies to species that are small, have high charge states, and are weakly polarizable.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] 'Soft' applies to species that are large, have low charge states and are strongly polarizable.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Acids and bases interact, and the most stable interactions are hard–hard and soft–soft.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This theory has found use in organic and inorganic chemistry.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Drago is a quantitative model that describes and predicts the strength of Lewis acid base interactions, −Δ*H*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The model assigned E and C parameters to many Lewis acids and bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Each acid is characterized by an *E*A and a *C*A.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Each base is likewise characterized by its own *E*B and *C*B.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The E and C parameters refer, respectively, to the electrostatic and covalent contributions to the strength of the bonds that the acid and base will form.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The W term represents a constant energy contribution for acid–base reaction such as the cleavage of a dimeric acid or base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The equation predicts reversal of acids and base strengths.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The graphical presentations of the equation show that there is no single order of Lewis base strengths or Lewis acid strengths.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The reaction of a strong acid with a strong base is essentially a quantitative reaction.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In this reaction both the sodium and chloride ions are spectators as the neutralization reaction, ${\ce {H+ + OH- -> H2O}}$ does not involve them.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] With weak bases addition of acid is not quantitative because a solution of a weak base is a buffer solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A solution of a weak acid is also a buffer solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] When a weak acid reacts with a weak base an equilibrium mixture is produced.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The notation [X] signifies "concentration of X".
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] An acid–alkali reaction is a special case of an acid–base reaction, where the base used is also an alkali.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] When an acid reacts with an alkali salt (a metal hydroxide), the product is a metal salt and water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Acid–alkali reactions are also neutralization reactions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Acids are in general pure substances that contain hydrogen cations (H+) or cause them to be produced in solutions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Hydrochloric acid (HCl) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4) are common examples.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, an **acid dissociation constant** (also known as **acidity constant**, or **acid-ionization constant**; denoted ⁠ $K_{a}$ ⁠) is a quantitative measure of the strength of an acid in solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] known as dissociation in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The chemical species HA is an acid that dissociates into A−, called the conjugate base of the acid, and a hydrogen ion, H+.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The system is said to be in equilibrium when the concentrations of its components do not change over time, because both forward and backward reactions are occurring at the same rate.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where quantities in square brackets represent the molar concentrations of the species at equilibrium.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, a hypothetical weak acid having *K*a = 10−5, the value of log *K*a is the exponent (−5), giving p*K*a = 5.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A lower *K*a corresponds to a weaker acid (an acid that is less dissociated at equilibrium).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The form p*K*a is often used because it provides a convenient logarithmic scale, and a lower p*K*a corresponds to a stronger acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid dissociation constant for an acid is a direct consequence of the underlying thermodynamics of the dissociation reaction; the p*K*a value is directly proportional to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the reaction.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of the p*K*a changes with temperature and can be understood qualitatively based on Le Chatelier's principle: when the reaction is endothermic, *K*a increases and p*K*a decreases with increasing temperature; the opposite is true for exothermic reactions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of p*K*a also depends on molecular structure of the acid in many ways.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, Linus Pauling proposed two rules: one for successive p*K*a of polyprotic acids (see Polyprotic acids below), and one to estimate the p*K*a of oxyacids based on the number of =O and −OH groups (see Factors that affect p*K*a values below).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other structural factors that influence the magnitude of the acid dissociation constant include inductive effects, mesomeric effects, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hammett type equations have frequently been applied to the estimation of p*K*a.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantitative behaviour of acids and bases in solution can be understood only if their p*K*a values are known.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In particular, the pH of a solution can be predicted when the analytical concentration and p*K*a values of all acids and bases are known; conversely, it is possible to calculate the equilibrium concentration of the acids and bases in solution when the pH is known.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These calculations find application in many different areas of chemistry, biology, medicine, and geology.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, many compounds used for medication are weak acids or bases, and a knowledge of the p*K*a values, together with the octanol-water partition coefficient, can be used for estimating the extent to which the compound enters the blood stream.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acid dissociation constants are also essential in aquatic chemistry and chemical oceanography, where the acidity of water plays a fundamental role.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In living organisms, acid–base homeostasis and enzyme kinetics are dependent on the p*K*a values of the many acids and bases present in the cell and in the body.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, a knowledge of p*K*a values is necessary for the preparation of buffer solutions and is also a prerequisite for a quantitative understanding of the interaction between acids or bases and metal ions to form complexes.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Experimentally, p*K*a values can be determined by potentiometric (pH) titration, but for values of p*K*a less than about 2 or more than about 11, spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be required due to practical difficulties with pH measurements.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constant for this dissociation reaction is known as a dissociation constant.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid loses a proton, leaving a conjugate base; the proton is transferred to the base, creating a conjugate acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions of an acid HA, the base is water; the conjugate base is A− and the conjugate acid is the hydronium ion.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Brønsted–Lowry definition applies to other solvents, such as dimethyl sulfoxide: the solvent S acts as a base, accepting a proton and forming the conjugate acid SH+.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In solution chemistry, it is common to use H+ as an abbreviation for the solvated hydrogen ion, regardless of the solvent.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated hydronium ion rather than a proton.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The designation of an acid or base as "conjugate" depends on the context.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The hydroxide ion OH−, a well known base, is here acting as the conjugate base of the acid water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acids and bases are thus regarded simply as donors and acceptors of protons respectively.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A broader definition of acid dissociation includes hydrolysis, in which protons are produced by the splitting of water molecules.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Lewis's original definition, an acid is a substance that accepts an electron pair to form a coordinate covalent bond.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid dissociation constant is a particular example of an equilibrium constant.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $\{X\}$ represents the activity, at equilibrium, of the chemical species X. $K^{\ominus }$ is dimensionless since activity is dimensionless.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Activities of the products of dissociation are placed in the numerator, activities of the reactants are placed in the denominator.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] See activity coefficient for a derivation of this expression.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $[{\text{HA}}]$ represents the concentration of HA and ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ is a quotient of activity coefficients.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To avoid the complications involved in using activities, dissociation constants are determined, where possible, in a medium of high ionic strength, that is, under conditions in which ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ can be assumed to be always constant.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the medium might be a solution of 0.1 molar (M) sodium nitrate or 3 M potassium perchlorate.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note, however, that all published dissociation constant values refer to the specific ionic medium used in their determination and that different values are obtained with different conditions, as shown for acetic acid in the illustration above.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When published constants refer to an ionic strength other than the one required for a particular application, they may be adjusted by means of specific ion theory (SIT) and other theories.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that in the context of metal-ligand complex formation, the equilibrium constants for the formation of metal complexes are usually defined as *association* constants.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In that case, the equilibrium constants for ligand protonation are also defined as association constants.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When discussing the properties of acids it is usual to specify equilibrium constants as acid dissociation constants, denoted by *K*a, with numerical values given the symbol p*K*a.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the other hand, association constants are used for bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, general purpose computer programs that are used to derive equilibrium constant values from experimental data use association constants for both acids and bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because stability constants for a metal-ligand complex are always specified as association constants, ligand protonation must also be specified as an association reaction.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The association constant for the formation of a supramolecular complex may be denoted as Ka; in such cases "a" stands for "association", not "acid".
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For polyprotic acids, the numbering of stepwise association constants is the reverse of the numbering of the dissociation constants.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] ⁠ R ⁠ is the gas constant and ⁠ T ⁠ is the absolute temperature.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus, for exothermic reactions, the standard enthalpy change, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠, is negative and *K* decreases with temperature.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For endothermic reactions, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ is positive and *K* increases with temperature.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where ⁠ $\Delta C_{p}$ ⁠ is the heat capacity change at constant pressure.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ may be taken to be constant over a small temperature range.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express each concentration value as the ratio c/c0, where c0 is the concentration in a [hypothetical] standard state, with a numerical value of 1, by definition.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express the concentrations on the mole fraction scale.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since mole fraction has no dimension, the quotient of concentrations will, by definition, be a pure number.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first and second options above give identical numerical values for an equilibrium constant.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is common practice in biochemistry to quote a value with a dimension as, for example, "*K*a = 30 mM" in order to indicate the scale, millimolar (mM) or micromolar (μM) of the concentration values used for its calculation.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid is classified as "strong" when the concentration of its undissociated species is too low to be measured.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Any aqueous acid with a p*K*a value of less than 0 is almost completely deprotonated and is considered a *strong acid*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] All such acids transfer their protons to water and form the solvent cation species (H3O+ in aqueous solution) so that they all have essentially the same acidity, a phenomenon known as solvent leveling.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They are said to be *fully dissociated* in aqueous solution because the amount of undissociated acid, in equilibrium with the dissociation products, is below the detection limit.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Likewise, any aqueous base with an association constant p*K*b less than about 0, corresponding to p*K*a greater than about 14, is leveled to OH− and is considered a *strong base*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nitric acid, with a p*K* value of around −1.7, behaves as a strong acid in aqueous solutions with a pH greater than 1.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At lower pH values it behaves as a weak acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values for strong acids have been estimated by theoretical means.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the p*K*a value of aqueous HCl has been estimated as −9.3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation, from which the following conclusions can be drawn.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In water, measurable p*K*a values range from about −2 for a strong acid to about 12 for a very weak acid (or strong base).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A buffer solution of a desired pH can be prepared as a mixture of a weak acid and its conjugate base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice, the mixture can be created by dissolving the acid in water, and adding the requisite amount of strong acid or base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the p*K*a and analytical concentration of the acid are known, the extent of dissociation and pH of a solution of a monoprotic acid can be easily calculated using an ICE table.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A polyprotic acid is a compound which may lose more than 1 proton.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Stepwise dissociation constants are each defined for the loss of a single proton.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The constant for dissociation of the first proton may be denoted as *K*a1 and the constants for dissociation of successive protons as *K*a2, etc.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Phosphoric acid, H3PO4, is an example of a polyprotic acid as it can lose three protons.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The species distribution diagram shows that the concentrations of the two ions are maximum at pH 5.5 and 10.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the difference between successive p*K* values is less than about four there is overlap between the pH range of existence of the species in equilibrium.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The smaller the difference, the more the overlap.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The case of citric acid is shown at the right; solutions of citric acid are buffered over the whole range of pH 2.5 to 7.5.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Pauling's first rule, successive p*K* values of a given acid increase (p*K*a2 > p*K*a1).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For oxyacids with more than one ionizable hydrogen on the same atom, the p*K*a values often increase by about 5 units for each proton removed, as in the example of phosphoric acid above.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It can be seen in the table above that the second proton is removed from a negatively charged species.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since the proton carries a positive charge extra work is needed to remove it, which is why p*K*a2 is greater than p*K*a1. p*K*a3 is greater than p*K*a2 because there is further charge separation.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When an exception to Pauling's rule is found, it indicates that a major change in structure is also occurring.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case of VO+2(aq), the vanadium is octahedral, 6-coordinate, whereas vanadic acid is tetrahedral, 4-coordinate.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This means that four "particles" are released with the first dissociation, but only two "particles" are released with the other dissociations, resulting in a much greater entropy contribution to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the first reaction than for the others.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For substances in solution, the isoelectric point (p*I*) is defined as the pH at which the sum, weighted by charge value, of concentrations of positively charged species is equal to the weighted sum of concentrations of negatively charged species.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case that there is one species of each type, the isoelectric point can be obtained directly from the p*K* values.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Take the example of glycine, defined as AH.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] There are two dissociation equilibria to consider.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*I* values for amino acids are listed at proteinogenic amino acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When more than two charged species are in equilibrium with each other a full speciation calculation may be needed.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When *K*a, *K*b and *K*w are determined under the same conditions of temperature and ionic strength, it follows, taking cologarithms, that p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] with sufficient accuracy for most practical purposes.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In effect there is no need to define p*K*b separately from p*K*a, but it is done here as often only p*K*b values can be found in the older literature.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the reciprocal of an association constant for formation of the complex.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because the relationship p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a holds only in aqueous solutions (though analogous relationships apply for other amphoteric solvents), subdisciplines of chemistry like organic chemistry that usually deal with nonaqueous solutions generally do not use p*K*b as a measure of basicity.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Instead, the p*K*a of the conjugate acid, denoted by p*K*aH, is quoted when basicity needs to be quantified.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A higher value for p*K*aH corresponds to a stronger base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the values p*K*aH (C5H5N) = 5.25 and p*K*aH ((CH3CH2)3N) = 10.75 indicate that (CH3CH2)3N (triethylamine) is a stronger base than C5H5N (pyridine).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amphoteric substance is one that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Carbonic acid equilibria are important for acid–base homeostasis in the human body.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amino acid is also amphoteric with the added complication that the neutral molecule is subject to an internal acid–base equilibrium in which the basic amino group attracts and binds the proton from the acidic carboxyl group, forming a zwitterion.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At pH less than about 5 both the carboxylate group and the amino group are protonated.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At high pH a second dissociation may take place.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus the amino acid molecule is amphoteric because it may either be protonated or deprotonated.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The water molecule may either gain or lose a proton.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where in aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated proton.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Often this is written as the hydronium ion H3O+, but this formula is not exact because in fact there is solvation by more than one water molecule and species such as H5O+2, H7O+3, and H9O+4 are also present.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The self-ionization constant of water, *K*w, is thus just a special case of an acid dissociation constant.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At that temperature both hydrogen and hydroxide ions have a concentration of 10−7 M.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high donor number, making it a strong Lewis base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high dielectric constant (relative permittivity), making it a good solvent for ionic species.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values of organic compounds are often obtained using the aprotic solvents dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and acetonitrile (ACN).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] DMSO is widely used as an alternative to water because it has a lower dielectric constant than water, and is less polar and so dissolves non-polar, hydrophobic substances more easily.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a measurable p*K*a range of about 1 to 30.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acetonitrile is less basic than DMSO, and, so, in general, acids are weaker and bases are stronger in this solvent.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Some p*K*a values at 25 °C for acetonitrile (ACN) and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). are shown in the following tables.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Values for water are included for comparison.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ionization of acids is less in an acidic solvent than in water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, hydrogen chloride is a weak acid when dissolved in acetic acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is because acetic acid is a much weaker base than water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The unlikely geminal diol species CH3C(OH)+2 is stable in these environments.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions the pH scale is the most convenient acidity function.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other acidity functions have been proposed for non-aqueous media, the most notable being the Hammett acidity function, *H*0, for superacid media and its modified version *H*− for superbasic media.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aprotic solvents, oligomers, such as the well-known acetic acid dimer, may be formed by hydrogen bonding.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid may also form hydrogen bonds to its conjugate base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This process, known as homoconjugation, has the effect of enhancing the acidity of acids, lowering their effective p*K*a values, by stabilizing the conjugate base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Homoconjugation enhances the proton-donating power of toluenesulfonic acid in acetonitrile solution by a factor of nearly 800.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solutions, homoconjugation does not occur, because water forms stronger hydrogen bonds to the conjugate base than does the acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a compound has limited solubility in water it is common practice (in the pharmaceutical industry, for example) to determine p*K*a values in a solvent mixture such as water/dioxane or water/methanol, in which the compound is more soluble.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the example shown at the right, the p*K*a value rises steeply with increasing percentage of dioxane as the dielectric constant of the mixture is decreasing.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A p*K*a value obtained in a mixed solvent cannot be used directly for aqueous solutions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this is that when the solvent is in its standard state its activity is *defined* as one.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the standard state of water:dioxane mixture with 9:1 mixing ratio is precisely that solvent mixture, with no added solutes.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To obtain the p*K*a value for use with aqueous solutions it has to be extrapolated to zero co-solvent concentration from values obtained from various co-solvent mixtures.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These facts are obscured by the omission of the solvent from the expression that is normally used to define p*K*a, but p*K*a values obtained in a *given* mixed solvent can be compared to each other, giving relative acid strengths.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The same is true of p*K*a values obtained in a particular non-aqueous solvent such a DMSO.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A universal, solvent-independent, scale for acid dissociation constants has not been developed, since there is no known way to compare the standard states of two different solvents.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Pauling's second rule is that the value of the first p*K*a for acids of the formula XO*m*(OH)*n* depends primarily on the number of oxo groups *m*, and is approximately independent of the number of hydroxy groups *n*, and also of the central atom X.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alternatively, various numerical formulas have been proposed including p*K*a = 8 − 5*m* (known as Bell's rule), p*K*a = 7 − 5*m*, or p*K*a = 9 − 7*m*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The dependence on *m* correlates with the oxidation state of the central atom, X: the higher the oxidation state the stronger the oxyacid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, p*K*a for HClO is 7.2, for HClO2 is 2.0, for HClO3 is −1 and HClO4 is a strong acid (p*K*a ≪ 0).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The increased acidity on adding an oxo group is due to stabilization of the conjugate base by delocalization of its negative charge over an additional oxygen atom.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This rule can help assign molecular structure: for example, phosphorous acid, having molecular formula H3PO3, has a p*K*a near 2, which suggested that the structure is HPO(OH)2, as later confirmed by NMR spectroscopy, and not P(OH)3, which would be expected to have a p*K*a near 8.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Inductive effects and mesomeric effects affect the p*K*a values.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A simple example is provided by the effect of replacing the hydrogen atoms in acetic acid by the more electronegative chlorine atom.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The electron-withdrawing effect of the substituent makes ionisation easier, so successive p*K*a values decrease in the series 4.7, 2.8, 1.4, and 0.7 when 0, 1, 2, or 3 chlorine atoms are present.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Hammett equation, provides a general expression for the effect of substituents.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alcohols do not normally behave as acids in water, but the presence of a double bond adjacent to the OH group can substantially decrease the p*K*a by the mechanism of keto–enol tautomerism.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ascorbic acid is an example of this effect.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The diketone 2,4-pentanedione (acetylacetone) is also a weak acid because of the keto–enol equilibrium.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aromatic compounds, such as phenol, which have an OH substituent, conjugation with the aromatic ring as a whole greatly increases the stability of the deprotonated form.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Structural effects can also be important.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The difference between fumaric acid and maleic acid is a classic example.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid is (E)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid, a *trans* isomer, whereas maleic acid is the corresponding *cis* isomer, i.e.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (Z)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid (see cis-trans isomerism).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid has p*K*a values of approximately 3.0 and 4.5.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] By contrast, maleic acid has p*K*a values of approximately 1.5 and 6.5.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this large difference is that when one proton is removed from the *cis* isomer (maleic acid) a strong intramolecular hydrogen bond is formed with the nearby remaining carboxyl group.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This favors the formation of the maleate H+, and it opposes the removal of the second proton from that species.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the *trans* isomer, the two carboxyl groups are always far apart, so hydrogen bonding is not observed.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Proton sponge, 1,8-bis(dimethylamino)naphthalene, has a p*K*a value of 12.1.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is one of the strongest amine bases known.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The high basicity is attributed to the relief of strain upon protonation and strong internal hydrogen bonding.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Effects of the solvent and solvation should be mentioned also in this section.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It turns out, these influences are more subtle than that of a dielectric medium mentioned above.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the expected (by electronic effects of methyl substituents) and observed in gas phase order of basicity of methylamines, Me3N > Me2NH > MeNH2 > NH3, is changed by water to Me2NH > MeNH2 > Me3N > NH3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Neutral methylamine molecules are hydrogen-bonded to water molecules mainly through one acceptor, N–HOH, interaction and only occasionally just one more donor bond, NH–OH2.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hence, methylamines are stabilized to about the same extent by hydration, regardless of the number of methyl groups.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In stark contrast, corresponding methylammonium cations always utilize **all** the available protons for donor NH–OH2 bonding.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Relative stabilization of methylammonium ions thus decreases with the number of methyl groups explaining the order of water basicity of methylamines.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The standard enthalpy change can be determined by calorimetry or by using the van 't Hoff equation, though the calorimetric method is preferable.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When both the standard enthalpy change and acid dissociation constant have been determined, the standard entropy change is easily calculated from the equation above.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the following table, the entropy terms are calculated from the experimental values of p*K*a and Δ*H*⊖.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The data were critically selected and refer to 25 °C and zero ionic strength, in water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first point to note is that, when p*K*a is positive, the standard free energy change for the dissociation reaction is also positive.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Second, some reactions are exothermic and some are endothermic, but, when Δ*H*⊖ is negative *T*ΔS⊖ is the dominant factor, which determines that Δ*G*⊖ is positive.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Last, the entropy contribution is always unfavourable (Δ*S*⊖ < 0) in these reactions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ions in aqueous solution tend to orient the surrounding water molecules, which orders the solution and decreases the entropy.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The contribution of an ion to the entropy is the partial molar entropy which is often negative, especially for small or highly charged ions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The ionization of a neutral acid involves formation of two ions so that the entropy decreases (Δ*S*⊖ < 0).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the second ionization of the same acid, there are now three ions and the anion has a charge, so the entropy again decreases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that the *standard* free energy change for the reaction is for the changes *from* the reactants in their standard states *to* the products in their standard states.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The free energy change *at* equilibrium is zero since the chemical potentials of reactants and products are equal at equilibrium.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The experimental determination of p*K*a values is commonly performed by means of titrations, in a medium of high ionic strength and at constant temperature.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A typical procedure would be as follows.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A solution of the compound in the medium is acidified with a strong acid to the point where the compound is fully protonated.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The solution is then titrated with a strong base until all the protons have been removed.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At each point in the titration pH is measured using a glass electrode and a pH meter.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constants are found by fitting calculated pH values to the observed values, using the method of least squares.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The total volume of added strong base should be small compared to the initial volume of titrand solution in order to keep the ionic strength nearly constant.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This will ensure that p*K*a remains invariant during the titration.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A calculated titration curve for oxalic acid is shown at the right.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Oxalic acid has p*K*a values of 1.27 and 4.27.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Therefore, the buffer regions will be centered at about pH 1.3 and pH 4.3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The buffer regions carry the information necessary to get the p*K*a values as the concentrations of acid and conjugate base change along a buffer region.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Between the two buffer regions there is an end-point, or equivalence point, at about pH 3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This end-point is not sharp and is typical of a diprotic acid whose buffer regions overlap by a small amount: p*K*a2 − p*K*a1 is about three in this example.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (If the difference in p*K* values were about two or less, the end-point would not be noticeable.) The second end-point begins at about pH 6.3 and is sharp.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This indicates that all the protons have been removed.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When this is so, the solution is not buffered and the pH rises steeply on addition of a small amount of strong base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, the pH does not continue to rise indefinitely.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A new buffer region begins at about pH 11 (p*K*w − 3), which is where self-ionization of water becomes important.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is very difficult to measure pH values of less than two in aqueous solution with a glass electrode, because the Nernst equation breaks down at such low pH values.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To determine p*K* values of less than about 2 or more than about 11 spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be used instead of, or combined with, pH measurements.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the glass electrode cannot be employed, as with non-aqueous solutions, spectrophotometric methods are frequently used.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These may involve absorbance or fluorescence measurements.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In both cases the measured quantity is assumed to be proportional to the sum of contributions from each photo-active species; with absorbance measurements the Beer–Lambert law is assumed to apply.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC) may be used to determine both a p*K* value and the corresponding standard enthalpy for acid dissociation.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Software to perform the calculations is supplied by the instrument manufacturers for simple systems.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Aqueous solutions with normal water cannot be used for 1H NMR measurements but heavy water, D2O, must be used instead.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] 13C NMR data, however, can be used with normal water and 1H NMR spectra can be used with non-aqueous media.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantities measured with NMR are time-averaged chemical shifts, as proton exchange is fast on the NMR time-scale.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other chemical shifts, such as those of 31P can be measured.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For some polyprotic acids, dissociation (or association) occurs at more than one nonequivalent site, and the observed macroscopic equilibrium constant, or macro-constant, is a combination of micro-constants involving distinct species.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When one reactant forms two products in parallel, the macro-constant is a sum of two micro-constants, $K=K_{X}+K_{Y}.$ This is true for example for the deprotonation of the amino acid cysteine, which exists in solution as a neutral zwitterion HS−CH2−CH(NH+3)−COO−.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Similarly, a base such as spermine has more than one site where protonation can occur.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, mono-protonation can occur at a terminal −NH2 group or at internal −NH− groups.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The *K*b values for dissociation of spermine protonated at one or other of the sites are examples of micro-constants.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They cannot be determined directly by means of pH, absorbance, fluorescence or NMR measurements; a measured *K*b value is the sum of the K values for the micro-reactions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nevertheless, the site of protonation is very important for biological function, so mathematical methods have been developed for the determination of micro-constants.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a reactant undergoes two reactions in series, the macro-constant for the combined reaction is the product of the micro-constant for the two steps.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the quantitative treatment of systems involving acid–base equilibria in solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Many applications exist in biochemistry; for example, the p*K*a values of proteins and amino acid side chains are of major importance for the activity of enzymes and the stability of proteins.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Protein p*K*a values cannot always be measured directly, but may be calculated using theoretical methods.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions are used extensively to provide solutions at or near the physiological pH for the study of biochemical reactions; the design of these solutions depends on a knowledge of the p*K*a values of their components.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Important buffer solutions include MOPS, which provides a solution with pH 7.2, and tricine, which is used in gel electrophoresis.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffering is an essential part of acid base physiology including acid–base homeostasis, and is key to understanding disorders such as acid–base disorder.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The isoelectric point of a given molecule is a function of its p*K* values, so different molecules have different isoelectric points.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This permits a technique called isoelectric focusing, which is used for separation of proteins by 2-D gel polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions also play a key role in analytical chemistry.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] They are used whenever there is a need to fix the pH of a solution at a particular value.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Compared with an aqueous solution, the pH of a buffer solution is relatively insensitive to the addition of a small amount of strong acid or strong base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The buffer capacity of a simple buffer solution is largest when pH = p*K*a.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In acid–base extraction, the efficiency of extraction of a compound into an organic phase, such as an ether, can be optimised by adjusting the pH of the aqueous phase using an appropriate buffer.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] At the optimum pH, the concentration of the electrically neutral species is maximised; such a species is more soluble in organic solvents having a low dielectric constant than it is in water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This technique is used for the purification of weak acids and bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A pH indicator is a weak acid or weak base that changes colour in the transition pH range, which is approximately p*K*a ± 1.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The design of a universal indicator requires a mixture of indicators whose adjacent p*K*a values differ by about two, so that their transition pH ranges just overlap.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In pharmacology, ionization of a compound alters its physical behaviour and macro properties such as solubility and lipophilicity, log *p*).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, ionization of any compound will increase the solubility in water, but decrease the lipophilicity.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This is exploited in drug development to increase the concentration of a compound in the blood by adjusting the p*K*a of an ionizable group.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the understanding of coordination complexes, which are formed by the interaction of a metal ion, Mm+, acting as a Lewis acid, with a ligand, L, acting as a Lewis base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] To determine the equilibrium constant for this reaction, in which the ligand loses a proton, the p*K*a of the protonated ligand must be known.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In practice, the ligand may be polyprotic; for example EDTA4− can accept four protons; in that case, all p*K*a values must be known.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In addition, the metal ion is subject to hydrolysis, that is, it behaves as a weak acid, so the p*K* values for the hydrolysis reactions must also be known.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Assessing the hazard associated with an acid or base may require a knowledge of p*K*a values.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, hydrogen cyanide is a very toxic gas, because the cyanide ion inhibits the iron-containing enzyme cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Hydrogen cyanide is a weak acid in aqueous solution with a p*K*a of about 9.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In strongly alkaline solutions, above pH 11, say, it follows that sodium cyanide is "fully dissociated" so the hazard due to the hydrogen cyanide gas is much reduced.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] An acidic solution, on the other hand, is very hazardous because all the cyanide is in its acid form.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Ingestion of cyanide by mouth is potentially fatal, independently of pH, because of the reaction with cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In environmental science acid–base equilibria are important for lakes and rivers; for example, humic acids are important components of natural waters.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] There are multiple techniques to determine the p*K*a of a chemical, leading to some discrepancies between different sources.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Well measured values are typically within 0.1 units of each other.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Data presented here were taken at 25 °C in water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] More values can be found in the Thermodynamics section, above.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A table of p*K*a of carbon acids, measured in DMSO, can be found on the page on carbanions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] The **Brønsted–Lowry theory** (also called **proton theory of acids and bases**) is an acid–base reaction theory, developed independently in 1923 by physical chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted (in Denmark) and Thomas Martin Lowry (in the United Kingdom).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] The basic concept of this theory is that when an acid and a base react with each other, the acid forms its conjugate base, and the base forms its conjugate acid by exchange of a proton (the hydrogen cation, or H+).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] This theory generalises the Arrhenius theory.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] In the Arrhenius theory, acids are defined as substances that dissociate in aqueous solutions to give H+ (hydrogen cations or protons), while bases are defined as substances that dissociate or ionize in aqueous solutions to give OH− (hydroxide ions).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] In 1923, physical chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted in Denmark and Thomas Martin Lowry in England both independently proposed the theory named after them.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] In the Brønsted–Lowry theory acids and bases are defined by the way they react with each other, generalising them.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] This is best illustrated by an equilibrium equation.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] The equilibrium sign, ⇌, is used because the reaction can occur in both forward and backward directions (is reversible).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] The acid, HA, is a **proton donor** which can lose a proton to become its conjugate base, A−.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] The base, B, is a **proton acceptor** which can become its conjugate acid, HB+.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Most acid–base reactions are fast, so the substances in the reaction are usually in dynamic equilibrium with each other.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Acetic acid, CH3COOH, is an acid because it donates a proton to water (H2O) and becomes its conjugate base, the acetate ion (CH3COO−).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] H2O is a base because it accepts a proton from CH3COOH and becomes its conjugate acid, the hydronium ion (H3O+).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] The reverse of an acid–base reaction is also an acid–base reaction, between the conjugate acid of the base in the first reaction and the conjugate base of the acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] In the above example, ethanoate is the base of the reverse reaction and hydronium ion is the acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] One feature of the Brønsted–Lowry theory in contrast to Arrhenius theory is that it does not require an acid to dissociate.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] The essence of Brønsted–Lowry theory is that an acid is only such in relation to a base, and *vice versa*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Water is amphoteric as it can act as an acid or as a base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] In the image shown at the right one molecule of H2O acts as a base and gains H+ to become H3O+ while the other acts as an acid and loses H+ to become OH−.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Another example is illustrated by substances like aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Thus, the ammonium ion, NH+4, in liquid ammonia corresponds to the hydronium ion in water and the amide ion, NH−2 in ammonia, to the hydroxide ion in water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Ammonium salts behave as acids, and metal amides behave as bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Some non-aqueous solvents can behave as bases, i.e. accept protons, in relation to Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] The most important of such solvents are dimethylsulfoxide, DMSO, and acetonitrile, CH3CN, as these solvents have been widely used to measure the acid dissociation constants of carbon-containing molecules.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Because DMSO accepts protons more strongly than H2O the acid becomes stronger in this solvent than in water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Indeed, many molecules behave as acids in non-aqueous solutions but not in aqueous solutions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] An extreme case occurs with carbon acids, where a proton is extracted from a C−H bond.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Some non-aqueous solvents can behave as acids.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] An acidic solvent will make dissolved substances more basic.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] For example, the compound CH3COOH is known as acetic acid since it behaves as an acid in water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] However, it behaves as a base in liquid hydrogen fluoride, a much more acidic solvent.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] In the same year that Brønsted and Lowry published their theory, G.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Lewis created an alternative theory of acid–base reactions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] The Lewis theory is based on electronic structure.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] A Lewis base is a compound that can give an electron pair to a Lewis acid, a compound that can accept an electron pair.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Lewis's proposal explains the Brønsted–Lowry classification using electronic structure.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] In this representation both the base, B, and the conjugate base, A−, are shown carrying a lone pair of electrons and the proton, which is a Lewis acid, is transferred between them.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] This is shown when the adduct H3N−BF3 forms from ammonia and boron trifluoride, a reaction that cannot occur in water because boron trifluoride is destroyed by water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] The reaction above illustrates that BF3 is an acid in both Lewis and Brønsted–Lowry classifications and shows that the theories agree with each other.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] In this case the acid does not split up but the base, H2O, does.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] A solution of B(OH)3 is acidic because hydrogen ions are given off in this reaction.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] and that, when dissolved in water, ammonia functions as a Lewis base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] The reactions between oxides in the solid or liquid states are excluded in the Brønsted–Lowry theory.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] is not covered in the Brønsted–Lowry definition of acids and bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] On the other hand, magnesium oxide acts as a base when it reacts with an aqueous solution of an acid (instead, the reaction can be considered a lewis acid-base reaction).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] Dissolved silicon dioxide, SiO2, has been predicted to be a weak acid in the Brønsted–Lowry sense.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] According to the Lux–Flood theory, oxides like MgO and SiO2 in the solid state may be called acids or bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/bronsted-lowry-acid-base-theory] For example, the mineral olivine may be known as a compound of a basic oxide, MgO, and silicon dioxide, SiO2, as an acidic oxide.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] A **buffer solution** is a solution where the pH does not change significantly on dilution or if an acid or base is added at constant temperature.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Its pH changes very little when a small amount of strong acid or base is added to it.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Buffer solutions are used as a means of keeping pH at a nearly constant value in a wide variety of chemical applications.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] In nature, there are many living systems that use buffering for pH regulation.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] For example, the bicarbonate buffering system is used to regulate the pH of blood, and bicarbonate also acts as a buffer in the ocean.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] When some strong acid is added to an equilibrium mixture of the weak acid and its conjugate base, hydrogen ions (H+) are added, and the equilibrium is shifted to the left, in accordance with Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Because of this, the hydrogen ion concentration increases by less than the amount expected for the quantity of strong acid added.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Similarly, if strong alkali is added to the mixture, the hydrogen ion concentration decreases by less than the amount expected for the quantity of alkali added.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] In Figure 1, the effect is illustrated by the simulated titration of a weak acid with p*K*a = 4.7.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The relative concentration of undissociated acid is shown in blue, and of its conjugate base in red.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The pH changes relatively slowly in the buffer region, pH = p*K*a ± 1, centered at pH = 4.7, where [HA] = [A−].
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Once the acid is more than 95% deprotonated, the pH rises rapidly because most of the added alkali is consumed in the neutralization reaction.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Buffer capacity is a quantitative measure of the resistance to change of pH of a solution containing a buffering agent with respect to a change of acid or alkali concentration.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] *K*w is the equilibrium constant for self-ionization of water, equal to 1.0×10−14.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Note that in solution H+ exists as the hydronium ion H3O+, and further aquation of the hydronium ion has negligible effect on the dissociation equilibrium, except at very high acid concentration.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] This equation shows that there are three regions of raised buffer capacity (see figure 2).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The pH of a solution containing a buffering agent can only vary within a narrow range, regardless of what else may be present in the solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] In biological systems this is an essential condition for enzymes to function correctly.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] For example, in human blood a mixture of carbonic acid (H 2CO 3) and bicarbonate (HCO− 3) is present in the plasma fraction; this constitutes the major mechanism for maintaining the pH of blood between 7.35 and 7.45.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Outside this narrow range (7.40 ± 0.05 pH unit), acidosis and alkalosis metabolic conditions rapidly develop, ultimately leading to death if the correct buffering capacity is not rapidly restored.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] If the pH value of a solution rises or falls too much, the effectiveness of an enzyme decreases in a process, known as denaturation, which is usually irreversible.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The majority of biological samples that are used in research are kept in a buffer solution, often phosphate buffered saline (PBS) at pH 7.4.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] In industry, buffering agents are used in fermentation processes and in setting the correct conditions for dyes used in colouring fabrics.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] They are also used in chemical analysis and calibration of pH meters.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] For buffers in acid regions, the pH may be adjusted to a desired value by adding a strong acid such as hydrochloric acid to the particular buffering agent.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] For alkaline buffers, a strong base such as sodium hydroxide may be added.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Alternatively, a buffer mixture can be made from a mixture of an acid and its conjugate base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] For example, an acetate buffer can be made from a mixture of acetic acid and sodium acetate.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Similarly, an alkaline buffer can be made from a mixture of the base and its conjugate acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] By combining substances with p*K*a values differing by only two or less and adjusting the pH, a wide range of buffers can be obtained.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Citric acid is a useful component of a buffer mixture because it has three p*K*a values, separated by less than two.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The buffer range can be extended by adding other buffering agents.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The following mixtures (McIlvaine's buffer solutions) have a buffer range of pH 3 to 8.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] A mixture containing citric acid, monopotassium phosphate, boric acid, and diethyl barbituric acid can be made to cover the pH range 2.6 to 12.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Other universal buffers are the Carmody buffer and the Britton–Robinson buffer, developed in 1931.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] For effective range see Buffer capacity, above.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Also see Good's buffers for the historic design principles and favourable properties of these buffer substances in biochemical applications.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] This shows that when the acid dissociates, equal amounts of hydrogen ion and anion are produced.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The equilibrium concentrations of these three components can be calculated in an ICE table (ICE standing for "initial, change, equilibrium").
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The first row, labelled **I**, lists the initial conditions: the concentration of acid is *C*0, initially undissociated, so the concentrations of A− and H+ would be zero; *y* is the initial concentration of *added* strong acid, such as hydrochloric acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] If strong alkali, such as sodium hydroxide, is added, then *y* will have a negative sign because alkali removes hydrogen ions from the solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The second row, labelled **C** for "change", specifies the changes that occur when the acid dissociates.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The acid concentration decreases by an amount −*x*, and the concentrations of A− and H+ both increase by an amount +*x*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] This follows from the equilibrium expression.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The third row, labelled **E** for "equilibrium", adds together the first two rows and shows the concentrations at equilibrium.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] With specific values for *C*0, *K*a and *y*, this equation can be solved for *x*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Assuming that pH = −log10[H+], the pH can be calculated as pH = −log10(*x* + *y*).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Polyprotic acids are acids that can lose more than one proton.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The constant for dissociation of the first proton may be denoted as *K*a1, and the constants for dissociation of successive protons as *K*a2, etc.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Citric acid is an example of a polyprotic acid H3A, as it can lose three protons.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] When the difference between successive p*K*a values is less than about 3, there is overlap between the pH range of existence of the species in equilibrium.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] In the case of citric acid, the overlap is extensive and solutions of citric acid are buffered over the whole range of pH 2.5 to 7.5.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Calculation of the pH with a polyprotic acid requires a speciation calculation to be performed.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] The numbering of cumulative, overall constants is the reverse of the numbering of the stepwise, dissociation constants.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/buffer-solution] Cumulative association constants are used in general-purpose computer programs such as the one used to obtain the speciation diagram above.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] A **Lewis acid** is a chemical species that contains an empty orbital which is capable of accepting an electron pair from a Lewis base to form a Lewis adduct.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] A **Lewis base**, then, is any species that has a filled orbital containing an electron pair which is not involved in bonding but may form a dative bond with a Lewis acid to form a Lewis adduct.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] For example, NH3 is a Lewis base, because it can donate its lone pair of electrons.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Trimethylborane [(CH3)3B or Me3B] is a Lewis acid as it is capable of accepting a lone pair.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In a Lewis adduct, the Lewis acid and base share an electron pair furnished by the Lewis base, forming a dative bond.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In the context of a specific chemical reaction between NH3 and Me3B, a lone pair from NH3 will form a dative bond with the empty orbital of Me3B to form an adduct NH3•BMe3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Lewis acids and bases are named for the American physical chemist Gilbert N.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The terms *nucleophile* and *electrophile* are sometimes interchangeable with Lewis base and Lewis acid, respectively.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] These terms, especially their abstract noun forms *nucleophilicity* and *electrophilicity*, emphasize the kinetic aspect of reactivity, while the Lewis basicity and Lewis acidity emphasize the thermodynamic aspect of Lewis adduct formation.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In many cases, the interaction between the Lewis base and Lewis acid in a complex is indicated by an arrow indicating the Lewis base donating electrons toward the Lewis acid using the notation of a dative bond—for example, Me3B←NH3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] A center dot may also be used to represent a Lewis adduct, such as Me3B·NH3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Another example is boron trifluoride diethyl etherate, BF3·Et2O.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In a slightly different usage, the center dot is also used to represent hydrate coordination in various crystals, as in MgSO4·7H2O for hydrated magnesium sulfate, irrespective of whether the water forms a dative bond with the metal.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Moreover, in some cases (e.g., sulfoxides and amine oxides as R2S → O and R3N → O), the use of the dative bond arrow is just a notational convenience for avoiding the drawing of formal charges.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In general, however, the donor–acceptor bond is viewed as simply somewhere along a continuum between idealized covalent bonding and ionic bonding.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Lewis acids are diverse and the term is used loosely.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Simplest are those that react directly with the Lewis base, such as boron trihalides and the pentahalides of phosphorus, arsenic, and antimony.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In the same vein, CH+3 can be considered to be the Lewis acid in methylation reactions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] However, the methyl cation never occurs as a free species in the condensed phase, and methylation reactions by reagents like CH3I take place through the simultaneous formation of a bond from the nucleophile to the carbon and cleavage of the bond between carbon and iodine (SN2 reaction).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Textbooks disagree on this point: some asserting that alkyl halides are electrophiles but not Lewis acids, while others describe alkyl halides (e.g.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The IUPAC states that Lewis acids and Lewis bases react to form Lewis adducts, and defines electrophile as Lewis acids.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In this adduct, all four fluoride centres (or more accurately, ligands) are equivalent.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Both BF4− and BF3OMe2 are Lewis base adducts of boron trifluoride.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The variability of the colors of iodine solutions reflects the variable abilities of the solvent to form adducts with the Lewis acid I2.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Most compounds considered to be Lewis acids require an activation step prior to formation of the adduct with the Lewis base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Complex compounds such as Et3Al2Cl3 and AlCl3 are treated as trigonal planar Lewis acids but exist as aggregates and polymers that must be degraded by the Lewis base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] A simpler case is the formation of adducts of borane.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In this case, an intermediate B2H−7 can be isolated.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Many metal complexes serve as Lewis acids, but usually only after dissociating a more weakly bound Lewis base, often water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The proton (H+) is one of the strongest but is also one of the most complicated Lewis acids.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] It is convention to ignore the fact that a proton is heavily solvated (bound to solvent).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] A typical example of a Lewis acid in action is in the Friedel–Crafts alkylation reaction.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The key step is the acceptance by AlCl3 of a chloride ion lone-pair, forming AlCl−4 and creating the strongly acidic, that is, electrophilic, carbonium ion.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] A Lewis base is an atomic or molecular species where the highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) is highly localized.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Typical Lewis bases are conventional amines such as ammonia and alkyl amines.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Other common Lewis bases include pyridine and its derivatives.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The strength of Lewis basicity correlates with the *pKa* of the parent acid: acids with high *pKa*'s give good Lewis bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] As usual, a weaker acid has a stronger conjugate base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The strength of Lewis bases have been evaluated for various Lewis acids, such as I2, SbCl5, and BF3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Nearly all electron pair donors that form compounds by binding transition elements can be viewed ligands.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Thus, a large application of Lewis bases is to modify the activity and selectivity of metal catalysts.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Chiral Lewis bases, generally multidentate, confer chirality on a catalyst, enabling asymmetric catalysis, which is useful for the production of pharmaceuticals.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The industrial synthesis of the anti-hypertension drug mibefradil uses a chiral Lewis base (*R*-MeOBIPHEP), for example.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Lewis acids and bases are commonly classified according to their hardness or softness.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In this context hard implies small and nonpolarizable and soft indicates larger atoms that are more polarizable.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] For example, an amine will displace phosphine from the adduct with the acid BF3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In the same way, bases could be classified.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] For example, bases donating a lone pair from an oxygen atom are harder than bases donating through a nitrogen atom.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Although the classification was never quantified it proved to be very useful in predicting the strength of adduct formation, using the key concepts that hard acid—hard base and soft acid—soft base interactions are stronger than hard acid—soft base or soft acid—hard base interactions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Later investigation of the thermodynamics of the interaction suggested that hard—hard interactions are enthalpy favored, whereas soft—soft are entropy favored.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Many methods have been devised to evaluate and predict Lewis acidity.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Many are based on spectroscopic signatures such as shifts NMR signals or IR bands e.g. the Gutmann-Beckett method and the Childs method.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The ECW model is a quantitative model that describes and predicts the strength of Lewis acid base interactions, −Δ*H*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The model assigned *E* and *C* parameters to many Lewis acids and bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The *E* and *C* parameters refer, respectively, to the electrostatic and covalent contributions to the strength of the bonds that the acid and base will form.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The *W* term represents a constant energy contribution for acid–base reaction such as the cleavage of a dimeric acid or base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The graphical presentations of the equation show that there is no single order of Lewis base strengths or Lewis acid strengths. and that single property scales are limited to a smaller range of acids or bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In 1923, Lewis wrote: "An acid substance is one which can employ an electron lone pair from another molecule in completing the stable group of one of its own atoms." The Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory was published in the same year.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The two theories are distinct but complementary.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] A Lewis base is also a Brønsted–Lowry base, but a Lewis acid does not need to be a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The classification into hard and soft acids and bases (HSAB theory) followed in 1963.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The strength of Lewis acid-base interactions, as measured by the standard enthalpy of formation of an adduct can be predicted by the Drago–Wayland two-parameter equation.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Lewis had suggested in 1916 that two atoms are held together in a chemical bond by sharing a pair of electrons.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] When each atom contributed one electron to the bond, it was called a covalent bond.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] When both electrons come from one of the atoms, it was called a dative covalent bond or coordinate bond.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] For example, in the formation of an ammonium ion from ammonia and hydrogen the ammonia molecule donates a pair of electrons to the proton; the identity of the electrons is lost in the ammonium ion that is formed.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] Nevertheless, Lewis suggested that an electron-pair donor be classified as a base and an electron-pair acceptor be classified as acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] A more modern definition of a Lewis acid is an atomic or molecular species with a localized empty atomic or molecular orbital of low energy.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] This lowest-energy unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) can accommodate a pair of electrons.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] A Lewis base is often a Brønsted–Lowry base as it can donate a pair of electrons to H+; the proton is a Lewis acid as it can accept a pair of electrons.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] The conjugate base of a Brønsted–Lowry acid is also a Lewis base as loss of H+ from the acid leaves those electrons which were used for the A—H bond as a lone pair on the conjugate base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] However, a Lewis base can be very difficult to protonate, yet still react with a Lewis acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] For example, carbon monoxide is a very weak Brønsted–Lowry base but it forms a strong adduct with BF3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] In another comparison of Lewis and Brønsted–Lowry acidity by Brown and Kanner, 2,6-Di-*tert*-butylpyridine reacts to form the hydrochloride salt with HCl but does not react with BF3.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/lewis-acids-and-bases] This example demonstrates that steric factors, in addition to electron configuration factors, play a role in determining the strength of the interaction between the bulky di-*t*-butylpyridine and tiny proton.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In chemistry, **pH** (/piːˈheɪtʃ/ or /piːˈeɪtʃ/; *pee-AYCH*) is a logarithmic scale used to specify the acidity or basicity of aqueous solutions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Acidic solutions (solutions with higher concentrations of hydrogen (H+) cations) are measured to have lower pH values than basic or alkaline solutions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] While the origin of the symbol 'pH' can be traced back to its original inventor, and the 'H' refers clearly to hydrogen, the exact original meaning of the letter 'p' in pH is still disputed; it has since acquired a more general technical meaning that is used in numerous other contexts.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] where [H+] is the equilibrium molar concentration of H+ (in M = mol/L) in the solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] At 25 °C (77 °F), solutions of which the pH is less than 7 are acidic, and solutions of which the pH is greater than 7 are basic.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Solutions with a pH of 7 at 25 °C are neutral (i.e. have the same concentration of H+ ions as OH− ions, i.e. the same as pure water).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The neutral value of the pH depends on the temperature and is lower than 7 if the temperature increases above 25 °C.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The pH range is commonly given as 0 to 14, but a pH value can be less than 0 for very concentrated strong acids or greater than 14 for very concentrated strong bases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The pH scale is traceable to a set of standard solutions whose pH is established by international agreement.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Primary pH standard values are determined using a concentration cell with transference by measuring the potential difference between a hydrogen electrode and a standard electrode such as the silver chloride electrode.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The pH of aqueous solutions can be measured with a glass electrode and a pH meter or a color-changing indicator.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Measurements of pH are important in chemistry, agronomy, medicine, water treatment, and many other applications.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In 1909, the Danish chemist Søren Peter Lauritz Sørensen introduced the concept of pH at the Carlsberg Laboratory, originally using the notation "pH•", with H• as a subscript to the lowercase p.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The concept was later revised in 1924 to the modern pH to accommodate definitions and measurements in terms of electrochemical cells.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Sørensen did not explain why he used the letter p, and the exact meaning of the letter is still disputed.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Sørensen described a way of measuring pH using *potential* differences, and it represents the negative *power* of 10 in the concentration of hydrogen ions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The letter *p* could stand for the French *puissance,* German *Potenz,* or Danish *potens*, all meaning "power", or it could mean "potential".
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] All of these words start with the letter *p* in French, German, and Danish, which were the languages in which Sørensen published: Carlsberg Laboratory was French-speaking; German was the dominant language of scientific publishing; Sørensen was Danish.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] He also used the letter *q* in much the same way elsewhere in the paper, and he might have arbitrarily labelled the test solution "p" and the reference solution "q"; these letters are often paired with e4 then e5.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Some literature sources suggest that "pH" stands for the Latin term *pondus hydrogenii* (quantity of hydrogen) or *potentia hydrogenii* (power of hydrogen), although this is not supported by Sørensen's writings.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In modern chemistry, the p stands for "the negative decimal logarithm of", and is used in the term p*K*a for acid dissociation constants, so pH is "the negative decimal logarithm of H+ ion concentration", while pOH is "the negative decimal logarithm of OH− ion concentration".
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] American bacteriologist Alice Catherine Evans, who influenced dairying and food safety, credited William Mansfield Clark and colleagues, including herself, with developing pH measuring methods in the 1910s, which had a wide influence on laboratory and industrial use thereafter.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In her memoir, she does not mention how much, or how little, Clark and colleagues knew about Sørensen's work a few years prior.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The first electronic method for measuring pH was invented by Arnold Orville Beckman, a professor at the California Institute of Technology in 1934.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] It was in response to a request from the local citrus grower Sunkist, which wanted a better method for quickly testing the pH of lemons they were picking from their nearby orchards.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The pH of a solution is defined as the decimal logarithm of the reciprocal of the hydrogen ion activity, *a*H+.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] More precisely, the hydrogen ion activity is taken with respect to the unit molality Henrien standard state and can be described with the following expression: $a_{H^{+}}=a_{H+}^{(m)}=\gamma _{H^{+}}^{(m)}\cdot m_{H^{+}}$ , where $m_{H+}$ represents the molality of the hydrogen ions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The concept of pH was developed because ion-selective electrodes, which are used to measure pH, respond to activity.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] where *E* is a measured potential, *E*0 is the standard electrode potential, *R* is the molar gas constant, *T* is the thermodynamic temperature, *F* is the Faraday constant.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] For H+, the number of electrons transferred is one.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The electrode potential is proportional to pH when pH is defined in terms of activity.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The reference electrode may be a silver chloride electrode or a calomel electrode, and the hydrogen-ion selective electrode is a standard hydrogen electrode.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Firstly, the cell is filled with a solution of known hydrogen ion activity and the electromotive force, *E*S, is measured.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Then the electromotive force, *E*X, of the same cell containing the solution of unknown pH is measured.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The difference between the two measured electromotive force values is proportional to pH.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This method of calibration avoids the need to know the standard electrode potential.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The proportionality constant, 1/*z*, is ideally equal to ${\frac {F}{RT\ln {10}}}\$ , the "Nernstian slope".
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In practice, a glass electrode is used instead of the cumbersome hydrogen electrode.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] A combined glass electrode has an in-built reference electrode.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] It is calibrated against Buffer solutions of known hydrogen ion (H+) activity proposed by the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Two or more buffer solutions are used in order to accommodate the fact that the "slope" may differ slightly from ideal.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] To calibrate the electrode, it is first immersed in a standard solution, and the reading on a pH meter is adjusted to be equal to the standard buffer's value.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The reading from a second standard buffer solution is then adjusted using the "slope" control to be equal to the pH for that solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Further details, are given in the IUPAC recommendations.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] When more than two buffer solutions are used the electrode is calibrated by fitting observed pH values to a straight line with respect to standard buffer values.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Commercial standard buffer solutions usually come with information on the value at 25 °C and a correction factor to be applied for other temperatures.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The pH scale is logarithmic and therefore pH is a dimensionless quantity.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This was the original definition of Sørensen in 1909, which was superseded in favor of pH in 1924. [H] is the concentration of hydrogen ions, denoted [H+] in modern chemistry.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] More correctly, the thermodynamic activity of H+ (*a*H+) in dilute solution should be replaced by [H+]/*c*0, where the standard state concentration *c*0 = 1 mol/L.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This ratio is a pure number whose logarithm can be defined.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] It is possible to measure the concentration of hydrogen cations directly using an electrode calibrated in terms of hydrogen ion concentrations.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] One common method is to titrate a solution of known concentration of a strong acid with a solution of known concentration of strong base in the presence of a relatively high concentration of background electrolyte.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] By knowing the concentrations of the acid and base, the concentration of hydrogen cations can be calculated and the measured potential can be correlated with concentrations.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The calibration is usually carried out using a Gran plot.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This procedure makes the activity of hydrogen cations equal to the numerical value of concentration of these ions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The glass electrode (and other Ion selective electrodes) should be calibrated in a medium similar to the one being investigated.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] For instance, if one wishes to measure the pH of a seawater sample, the electrode should be calibrated in a solution resembling seawater in its chemical composition.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The difference between p[H] and pH is quite small, and it has been stated that pH = p[H] + 0.04.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] However, it is common practice to use the term "pH" for both types of measurement.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] pOH is sometimes used as a measure of the concentration of hydroxide ions, OH−.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] By definition, pOH is the negative logarithm (to the base 10) of the hydroxide ion concentration (mol/L). pOH values can be derived from pH measurements and vice-versa.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] where *K*W is the self-ionization constant of water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] (Under otherwise standard conditions, the equation is exact at approximately 24.87 °C.) However this relationship is not strictly valid in other circumstances, such as in measurements of soil alkalinity.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] pH can be measured using indicators, which change color depending on the pH of the solution they are in.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] By comparing the color of a test solution to a standard color chart, the pH can be estimated to the nearest whole number.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] For more precise measurements, the color can be measured using a colorimeter or spectrophotometer.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] A Universal indicator is a mixture of several indicators that can provide a continuous color change over a range of pH values, typically from about pH 2 to pH 10.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Universal indicator paper is made from absorbent paper that has been impregnated with a universal indicator.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] An alternative method of measuring pH is using an electronic pH meter, which directly measures the voltage difference between a pH-sensitive electrode and a reference electrode.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] pH values can be measured in non-aqueous solutions, but they are based on a different scale from aqueous pH values because the standard states used for calculating hydrogen ion concentrations (activities) are different.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] where *μ*H+ is the chemical potential of the hydrogen cation, $\mu _{{\ce {H+}}}^{\ominus }$ is its chemical potential in the chosen standard state, *R* is the molar gas constant and *T* is the thermodynamic temperature.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Therefore, pH values on the different scales cannot be compared directly because of differences in the solvated proton ions, such as lyonium ions, which require an insolvent scale that involves the transfer activity coefficient of hydronium/lyonium ion.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] pH is an example of an acidity function, but others can be defined.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] For example, the Hammett acidity function, *H*0, has been developed in connection with Superacids.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In 2010, a new approach to measuring pH was proposed, called the *unified absolute pH scale*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This approach allows for a common reference standard to be used across different solutions, regardless of their pH range.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The unified absolute pH scale is based on the absolute chemical potential of the hydrogen cation, as defined by the Lewis acid–base theory.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This scale applies to liquids, gases, and even solids.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The advantages of the unified absolute pH scale include consistency, accuracy, and applicability to a wide range of sample types.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] It is precise and versatile because it serves as a common reference standard for pH measurements.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] However, implementation efforts, compatibility with existing data, complexity, and potential costs are some challenges.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The measurement of pH can become difficult at extremely acidic or alkaline conditions, such as below pH 2.5 (ca.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This is due to the breakdown of the Nernst equation in such conditions when using a glass electrode.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Several factors contribute to this problem.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] First, liquid junction potentials may not be independent of pH.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Second, the high ionic strength of concentrated solutions can affect the electrode potentials.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] At high pH the glass electrode may be affected by "alkaline error", because the electrode becomes sensitive to the concentration of cations such as Na+ and K+ in the solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] To overcome these problems, specially constructed electrodes are available.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Runoff from mines or mine tailings can produce some extremely low pH values, down to −3.6.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Pure water has a pH of 7 at 25 °C, meaning it is neutral.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] When an acid is dissolved in water, the pH will be less than 7, while a base, or alkali, will have a pH greater than 7.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] A strong acid, such as hydrochloric acid, at concentration 1 mol/L has a pH of 0, while a strong alkali like sodium hydroxide, at the same concentration, has a pH of 14.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Since pH is a logarithmic scale, a difference of one in pH is equivalent to a tenfold difference in hydrogen ion concentration.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Neutrality is not exactly 7 at 25 °C, but 7 serves as a good approximation in most cases.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Neutrality occurs when the concentration of hydrogen cations ([H+]) equals the concentration of hydroxide ions ([OH−]), or when their activities are equal.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Since self-ionization of water holds the product of these concentration [H+] × [OH−] = *K*w, it can be seen that at neutrality [H+] = [OH−] = √*K*w, or pH = p*K*w/2. p*K*w is approximately 14 but depends on ionic strength and temperature, and so the pH of neutrality does also.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Pure water and a solution of NaCl in pure water are both neutral, since dissociation of water produces equal numbers of both ions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] However the pH of the neutral NaCl solution will be slightly different from that of neutral pure water because the hydrogen and hydroxide ions' activity is dependent on ionic strength, so *K*w varies with ionic strength.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] When pure water is exposed to air, it becomes mildly acidic.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This is because water absorbs carbon dioxide from the air, which is then slowly converted into bicarbonate and hydrogen cations (essentially creating carbonic acid).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Topsoil pH is influenced by soil parent material, erosional effects, climate and vegetation.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] A recent map of topsoil pH in Europe shows the alkaline soils in Mediterranean, Hungary, East Romania, North France.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Scandinavian countries, Portugal, Poland and North Germany have more acid soils.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Plants contain pH-dependent pigments that can be used as pH indicators, such as those found in hibiscus, red cabbage (anthocyanin), and grapes (red wine).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Citrus fruits have acidic juice primarily due to the presence of citric acid, while other carboxylic acids can be found in various living systems.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The protonation state of phosphate derivatives, including ATP, is pH-dependent.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Hemoglobin, an oxygen-transport enzyme, is also affected by pH in a phenomenon known as the Root effect.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The pH of seawater plays an important role in the ocean's carbon cycle.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] There is evidence of ongoing ocean acidification (meaning a drop in pH value): Between 1950 and 2020, the average pH of the ocean surface fell from approximately 8.15 to 8.05.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Carbon dioxide emissions from human activities are the primary cause of ocean acidification, with atmospheric carbon dioxide levels at 430 ppm CO2 at Mauna Loa observatory in 2025.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In 2024, the annual atmospheric CO2 increase measured by the NOAA’s Global Monitoring Laboratory was 3.75 ppm CO2/year.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] CO2 from the atmosphere is absorbed by the oceans.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This produces carbonic acid (H2CO3) which dissociates into a bicarbonate ion (HCO− 3) and a hydrogen cation (H+).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The presence of free hydrogen cations (H+) lowers the pH of the ocean.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The measurement of pH in seawater is complicated by the chemical properties of seawater, and three distinct pH scales exist in chemical oceanography.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In practical terms, the three seawater pH scales differ in their pH values up to 0.10, differences that are much larger than the accuracy of pH measurements typically required, in particular, in relation to the ocean's carbonate system.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Since it omits consideration of sulfate and fluoride ions, the *free scale* is significantly different from both the total and seawater scales.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Because of the relative unimportance of the fluoride ion, the total and seawater scales differ only very slightly.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] As part of its operational definition of the pH scale, the IUPAC defines a series of Buffer solutions across a range of pH values (often denoted with National Bureau of Standards (NBS) or National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) designation).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] These solutions have a relatively low ionic strength (≈ 0.1) compared to that of seawater (≈ 0.7), and, as a consequence, are not recommended for use in characterizing the pH of seawater, since the ionic strength differences cause changes in electrode potential.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] To resolve this problem, an alternative series of buffers based on artificial seawater was developed.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This new series resolves the problem of ionic strength differences between samples and the buffers, and the new pH scale is referred to as the *total scale*, often denoted as pHT.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The total scale was defined using a medium containing sulfate ions.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] An alternative scale, the *free scale*, often denoted pHF, omits this consideration and focuses solely on [H+]F, in principle making it a simpler representation of hydrogen ion concentration.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] However, it is difficult to estimate *K** S in seawater, limiting the utility of the otherwise more straightforward free scale.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Another scale, known as the *seawater scale*, often denoted pHSWS, takes account of a further protonation relationship between hydrogen cations and fluoride ions, H+ + F− ⇌ HF.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] However, the advantage of considering this additional complexity is dependent upon the abundance of fluoride in the medium.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In seawater, for instance, sulfate ions occur at much greater concentrations (> 400 times) than those of fluoride.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] As a consequence, for most practical purposes, the difference between the total and seawater scales is very small.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The pH level of food influences its flavor, texture, and shelf life.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Acidic foods, such as citrus fruits, tomatoes, and vinegar, typically have a pH below 4.6 with sharp and tangy taste, while basic foods taste bitter or soapy.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Maintaining the appropriate pH in foods is essential for preventing the growth of harmful microorganisms.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The alkalinity of vegetables such as spinach and kale can also influence their texture and color during cooking.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The pH also influences the Maillard reaction, which is responsible for the browning of food during cooking, impacting both flavor and appearance.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In living organisms, the pH of various body fluids, cellular compartments, and organs is tightly regulated to maintain a state of acid–base balance known as acid–base homeostasis.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Acidosis, defined by blood pH below 7.35, is the most common disorder of acid–base homeostasis and occurs when there is an excess of acid in the body.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In contrast, alkalosis is characterized by excessively high blood pH.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Blood pH is usually slightly alkaline, with a pH of 7.365, referred to as physiological pH in biology and medicine.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Plaque formation in teeth can create a local acidic environment that results in tooth decay through demineralization.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Enzymes and other proteins have an optimal pH range for function and can become inactivated or denatured outside this range.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] When calculating the pH of a solution containing acids or bases, a chemical speciation calculation is used to determine the concentration of all chemical species present in the solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The complexity of the procedure depends on the nature of the solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Strong acids and bases are compounds that are almost completely dissociated in water, which simplifies the calculation.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] However, for weak acids, a quadratic equation must be solved, and for weak bases, a cubic equation is required.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In general, a set of non-linear simultaneous equations must be solved.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Water itself is a weak acid and a weak base, so its dissociation must be taken into account at high pH and low solute concentration (see *Amphoterism*).
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] where [H+] stands for the concentration of the aqueous hydronium ion and [OH−] represents the concentration of the hydroxide ion.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This equilibrium needs to be taken into account at high pH and when the solute concentration is extremely low.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Strong acids and bases are compounds that are essentially fully dissociated in water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This means that in an acidic solution, the concentration of hydrogen cations (H+) can be considered equal to the concentration of the acid.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Similarly, in a basic solution, the concentration of hydroxide ions (OH−) can be considered equal to the concentration of the base.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The pH of a solution is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of H+, and the pOH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of OH−.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] For example, the pH of a 0.01 M solution of hydrochloric acid (HCl) is equal to 2 (pH = −log10(0.01)), while the pOH of a 0.01 M solution of sodium hydroxide (NaOH) is equal to 2 (pOH = −log10(0.01)), which corresponds to a pH of about 12.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] However, self-ionization of water must also be considered when concentrations of a strong acid or base is very low or high.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] For instance, a 5×10−8 M solution of HCl would be expected to have a pH of 7.3 based on the above procedure, which is incorrect as it is acidic and should have a pH of less than 7.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] In such cases, the system can be treated as a mixture of the acid or base and water, which is an amphoteric substance.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] By accounting for the self-ionization of water, the true pH of the solution can be calculated.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] For example, a 5×10−8 M solution of HCl would have a pH of 6.89 when treated as a mixture of HCl and water.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The self-ionization equilibrium of solutions of sodium hydroxide at higher concentrations must also be considered.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] A weak acid or the conjugate acid of a weak base can be treated using the same formalism.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] First, an acid dissociation constant is defined as follows.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] and its value is assumed to have been determined by experiment.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This being so, there are three unknown concentrations, [HA], [H+] and [A−] to determine by calculation.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] One way to provide them is to apply the law of mass conservation in terms of the two "reagents" H and A.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Solution of this quadratic equation gives the hydrogen ion concentration and hence p[H] or, more loosely, pH.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] This procedure is illustrated in an ICE table which can also be used to calculate the pH when some additional (strong) acid or alkaline has been added to the system, that is, when *C*A ≠ *C*H.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] For example, what is the pH of a 0.01 M solution of benzoic acid, p*K*a = 4.19?
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] For alkaline solutions, an additional term is added to the mass-balance equation for hydrogen.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Some systems, such as with polyprotic acids, are amenable to spreadsheet calculations.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] With three or more reagents or when many complexes are formed with general formulae such as ApBqHr, the following general method can be used to calculate the pH of a solution.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] For example, with three reagents, each equilibrium is characterized by an equilibrium constant, *β*.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] There are no approximations involved in these equations, except that each stability constant is defined as a quotient of concentrations, not activities.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Much more complicated expressions are required if activities are to be used.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] There are three simultaneous equations in the three unknowns, [A], [B] and [H].
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] Because the equations are non-linear and their concentrations may range over many powers of 10, the solution of these equations is not straightforward.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] However, many computer programs are available which can be used to perform these calculations.
[src:acid-base-chemistry/ph] The calculation of hydrogen ion concentrations, using this approach, is a key element in the determination of equilibrium constants by potentiometric titration.
